🧠 Core Idea (Intuition)

We want:
👉 All '*' (sheep) to become continuous (no gaps)

Equivalent:
👉 Move sheep so they occupy consecutive positions

❗ Important Observation

Instead of thinking:

“where should each sheep go?”

Think:

“what is the BEST block of consecutive positions?”

🔥 Key Insight — MEDIAN

👉 The optimal strategy is to align around the median sheep

Why?

Moving towards median minimizes total distance
Classic property:
👉 Sum of absolute distances is minimized at median
🧩 Step-by-Step Thinking
Step 1: Store positions of sheep

Example:

s = "*.*...*.**"
positions = [0,2,6,8,9]
Step 2: Find median sheep
mid index = cnt / 2

👉 This sheep does not move (anchor point)

Step 3: Decide final positions

If median is at position pos, then final arrangement will be:

pos - k, pos - k + 1, ..., pos, ..., pos + k

👉 Basically a continuous block centered at median

Step 4: Calculate starting point
start = pos - (cnt / 2)
Step 5: Move each sheep

For each sheep:

cost += abs(current_position - target_position)
💡 Why This Works
We preserve relative order of sheep
Avoid crossing (which increases cost)
Median minimizes total movement
⚡ Clean Formula View

If positions are:

p[0], p[1], ..., p[k-1]

Target positions:

start, start+1, ..., start+k-1

Cost:

sum |p[i] - (start + i)|
🔁 Code Mapping (Your Code Explained)
Step 1: Count sheep
ll cnt = count(begin(s), end(s), '*');
Step 2: Find median position
if(p == cnt/2) pos = i;

👉 pos = index of median sheep

Step 3: Compute start
ll start = pos - cnt/2;
Step 4: Compute cost
if(s[i] == '*') {
    ans += abs(start - i);
    start++;
}

👉 Assign next target position (start++)

🔁 Dry Run
Input:
s = "*.*...*.**"
positions = [0,2,6,8,9]
cnt = 5
median = index 2 → pos = 6
start = 6 - 2 = 4
target = [4,5,6,7,8]

Now:

|0-4| + |2-5| + |6-6| + |8-7| + |9-8|
= 4 + 3 + 0 + 1 + 1 = 9 ✅
